article.headline: Phoenix snaps three-game losing streak
article.linkText: Suns race to big lead, then outlast Sixers
article.story:
PHOENIX (AP) -- Phoenix coach Mike D'Antoni felt a familiar feeling overcoming him, and he wasn't comfortable with it. Stephon Marbury scored 16 of his 17 points in the first half to stake the Suns to a 19-point lead, and Phoenix held on to beat the Philadelphia 76ers 100-92 Sunday night. The Sixers pulled within three points late in the fourth quarter but couldn't complete the rally. "I didn't know if they sensed it, but I did," said D'Antoni, whose team squandered a 17-point lead in a loss to Boston on Friday. "Those thoughts do go through your mind. We've got to get our swagger back or you end up playing not to lose." Shawn Marion scored 26 points and Joe Johnson added 23 for the Suns, who snapped a three-game losing streak. The win was just the Suns' third in their last 13 games. "We kept our composure and kept attacking them," Marion said. "We've been playing with great energy but we need to sustain it for 48 minutes. Tonight we did that." Glenn Robinson had 23 points and nine rebounds and Eric Snow added 17 points for the Sixers, who were without Allen Iverson (swollen right knee) for the seventh consecutive game. Phoenix took a 66-55 lead on Johnson's 3-pointer with 6:04 left in the third period, only to watch Philadelphia steadily cut into it. Robinson and Greg Buckner scored on consecutive possessions to start the fourth quarter, and Kyle Korver capped a 6-0 run with a 20-foot jumper as the Sixers pulled to 78-74 with 6:12 remaining. Derrick Coleman sank a pair of free throws to make it 82-79 with 3:57 to go, and Philadelphia had a chance to tie the game moments later. But Robinson missed a 3-point attempt from the right wing and the Sixers never got closer than four the rest of the way. "We're kicking ourselves by spotting teams 10 and 12 points and trying to fight back," Robinson said. "Then we don't have the energy to finish the game. We have to start the games a little bit better." The Suns relied heavily on their outside shooting, connecting on nine of a season-high 23 3-point attempts. Marbury was 4-of-7 and Johnson 3-of-6 from beyond the arc. Philadelphia outscored Phoenix 40-26 in the paint. "If I'm open I've got to take what's given to me," said Marion, who was 2-of-6 on 3s and 7-of-20 overall. "It's not as easy to get to the basket as you think it is. It's hard to get the basket." Marbury and Jake Voskuhl combined for 14 points as the Suns opened an 18-8 lead. Phoenix stretched the lead to 35-19 on Marion's 3-pointer with 1.2 seconds left in the first quarter and took its biggest lead, 39-22, on Leandro Barbosa's layup with 9:24 to go in the first half. "The first quarter probably decided the game," D'Antoni said. "It was a big first quarter for us ... then we had a lull in the middle again. That is something that we definitely need to work on." Coleman scored 12 and Kenny Thomas added 10 points and six rebounds for the Sixers, who have lost four of five. "Our effort to start the game wasn't there," said Philadelphia coach Randy Ayers. "We turned the ball over early and got behind early in the game." Philadelphia's comeback efforts were hampered by 21-of-31 shooting from the free throw line, including a pair of second-quarter misses by Aaron McKie on attempted three-point plays.

Game notes
Philadelphia is 4-5 without Iverson in the lineup. ... Two of Phoenix's three centers, Jahidi White and Voskuhl, fouled out during a nine-second span of the fourth quarter. ... McKie re-aggravated a left hamstring injury in the first half and did not play after halftime. ... The Suns have won 15 of the last 17 meetings between the teams in Phoenix. ... Iverson has missed one of the two meetings between the teams in three of the last four seasons. ... The Suns used their 14th different starting lineup in 31 games, the same total as Phoenix used all of last season.
